          "body": "The chapter opens with the highest commendation given any king in the entire Deuteronomistic history: 'He trusted in the LORD, the God of Israel; so that after him there was none like him among all the kings of Judah, nor among those who were before him' (18:5). This is not hyperbole in the modern sense but a formal literary verdict — the narrator places Hezekiah above even Josiah (though 23:25 will make a parallel claim for Josiah on different grounds, the love of Torah). The commendation is followed by four concrete verbs: he removed, smashed, cut down, and broke in pieces. Hezekiah's faith is not theological sentiment; it produces iconoclasm. Notably, the Nehushtan incident (18:4) shows that even an artifact with Mosaic origin — the bronze serpent of Numbers 21:8-9 — can become an idol. When Israel burned incense to it rather than to the God who commanded Moses to make it, it ceased to be holy hardware and became an offense. Hezekiah names it dismissively: 'Nehushtan' — merely a piece of bronze (nachash + nechoshet). The commendation concludes with the Lord's presence and prosperity (18:7), but also with political boldness: Hezekiah 'rebelled against the king of Assyria and did not serve him' (18:7). Trust in God produces not quietism but the courage to break unjust political submission."
